ont><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=78.topic>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Nuclear spaceships</span><hr size=1> The nuclear spaceships that are likely to be used for<br>
spaceflights are:<br>
<br>
1 . solid core nuclear rockets<br>
<br>
2. nuclear electric rockets <br>
<br>
3. fusion microexplosion rockets <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uzaphod4468.showPublicProfile?language=EN>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 519<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/19/02 6:54 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=78.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/hitchhikers/gallery/images/100/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Nuclear spaceships</span><hr size=1> My vote is pulsed fusion:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <br>
The pulsed fusion concept works fairly simply: A fuel pellet is fired upon by high power laser beams, causing a fusion reaction. The fusion reaction products are directed, using magnetic fields, in a specific direction (i.e. the rear of the vehicle), causing thrust. Superconducting coils surround the exit port. As the fusion products pulse past these coils, they induce a current which is used to recharge the laser beams and the magnetic field. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://scientium.com/Commentary/Bowden_Essays/startrip/starship/rockets.htm#longshot">Project Longshot</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.frontvision.com/space/ss_fast.htm">Fast Interstellar Craft</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uyales.showPublicProfile?language=EN>yales</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Orion Commander</span><br>  Posts: 275<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(5/2/02 10:33 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=78.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.attbi.com/~yales/images/53invad2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Nuclear spaceships</span><hr size=1> But remember, only the first two actually exist (on the drawing boards, but at least utilizing tested technologies).<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/utmayes1999.showPublicProfile?language=EN>tmayes1999</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 90<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(5/2/02 4:36 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=78.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Nuclear spaceships</span><hr size=1> Solid core nuclear rockets have been successfully tested on the ground. Many electric engines have bee successfully used<br>
in space in the past on satallites, and the deep space 1<br>
probe. The soviets/ russians have successfully used nuclear<br>
reactor powered electric generators in space on their cosmos satallites for 30 years with up to 35 kilowatt power levels.<br>
Thus only fusion microexplosion drives actually remain only<br>
on the drawing board.<br>
Tim  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uyales.showPublicProfile?language=EN>yales</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Orion Commander</span><br>  Posts: 279<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(5/2/02 6:52 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=78.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.attbi.com/~yales/images/53invad2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Nuclear spaceships</span><hr size=1> Let me phrase myself more carefully.<br>
1) The only Solid core nuclear engines have been ground engineering test platforms. Actual space usable engines are only on the drawing boards.<br>
2) Space reactors have been tested, and ion drives have been tested, but never have a combined system been tested. They exist only on the drawing boards.<br>
<br>
3) Fusion drives are purely speculative and not on the drawing boards because issues of basic physics have not been resolved, let alone engineering designs.<br>
<br>
So recapping myself, 1 and 2, altho only on the drawing boards, are feasable,<br>
while 3 is only hope.<br>
<br>
yale <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ujohnfraz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>John Fraz</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://members.hometown.aol.com/_ht_a/naturyl/images/YinYangsblack.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 69<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(5/2/02 9:31 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=78.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Nuclear spaceships</span><hr size=1> For pulsed fusion, we shouldn't discount the ACMF. I know, anti-protons are lab curiosities, and long-term storage is even farther out.<br>
<br>
There's also Mag-Orion (the original message in this thread didn't even mention old-fashioned, brute force, dirty &amp; ugly, space use Orion. I'm hurt...<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  )<br>
<br>
 With what's offered, I'd have to follow Lewis &amp; <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://neofuel.com/">Zuppero</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->, and vote for solid core NTR (Dual mode, so it could be used for an ice-melter at an NEA as well as a power plant for the mission)<br>
<br>
 Actually, why not combine &amp; get the best of all possible worlds:<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  1)</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> CH4 burning NTR, with O2 afterburners for lifting off a big NEA or perigee-kick propulsive maneuvers<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  2)</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> NH3 fueled NTR for middle range performance<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  3)</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> H2O cooled power reactor for either NEP (low thrust, extreme efficiency NH3 fueled ion engine), or ice-melting mining probe.<br>
 Note that this triple-use capability makes a simple, old NTR into a full contender for the performance cited for semi-magical VASIMR... All parts of this have either been static-bench tested or lab tested (minus nuclear power), so it's not at all far out.<br>
<br>
 (Too many acronyms?) <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ujohnfraz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>John Fraz</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://members.hometown.aol.com/_ht_a/naturyl/images/YinYangsblack.gif" BORDER=0> at: 5/2/02 9:33:03 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uyales.showPublicProfile?language=EN>yales</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Orion Commander</span><br>  Posts: 287<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(5/2/02 9:48 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=78.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.attbi.com/~yales/images/53invad2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Nuclear spaceships</span><hr size=1> I agree on the potential of a VASIMR engine -whether solar or reactor energized.<br>
<br>
