I have mixed feelings about this. NTRs aren't much better than lab test items now. A few static tests is far from a useable manned ship.<br>
 We have <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> one</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> large-ish ion engine (actually it's tiny), and a bit of experience with using even smaller versions of them as station keeping/maneuvering thrusters.<br>
<br>
 There was one successful HE test article of detonation-impulse propulsion. Far cry from a test of a nuclear explosive powered model, yes.<br>
 There's actually a lot of lab experience with making sub-critical fuel pellets undergo rapid fission, and micro-fusion itself isn't as far out as VASIMR. The only uncertainty of ACMF is the antiproton storage. I submit that it's in the same category as VASIMR -in fact, they're both waiting on the same developments. If they can put VASIMR together, then we've got ACMF.<br>
<br>
 What tips the scales a bit farther towards NPR (space use, parts lofted by HLVs, if it's determined that the single HLV model puts too much waste products into the atmosphere), is the immense utility of it, and our extensive experience with a wide variety of nuclear explosives.<br>
 We know a hell of a lot about making things go <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>BOOM</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->, and NPR has capability to carry a heck of a lot of safety &amp; redundancy, and the performance is <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>absolutely</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> unparalleled by anything else on or off the drawing boards (except maybe ACMF, which is about as far out as VASIMR).<br>
